May 5, 1937
Manhattan.  Seventh Avenue - between 12th and 13th street.

Seventh Ave. (right), at the N.W. corner of West 12th Street (left) showing a northward view across a portion of the site upon which the "old Rhinelander Flats" stood until recently. The trees that stood in front of same still remain, shading playing children and hiding from view the two old Huguenot rear buildings at the rear of Nos. 204-06 West 13th Street. The peaked roof structure to the west of the latter is P.S. No. 16. This set consists of a positive and negative photostat of an original photograph that was discoloring in our files.

July 19, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

(1) Seventh Avenue, west side, at West 13th Street, showing the demolition of the 'Rhinelander Flats', a row of eleven 3-story brick houses with wooden balconies. These buildings, which were erected in 1848, extend from West 18th to 13th streets, and occupy the whole block front. This area will be cleared and developed into a temporary playground by the WPA. For further data, see the NY Sun of May 1, 1937.
May 7, 1937
PL Sperr

Seventh Avenue, east side, from W. 12th (left of No. 3) to W. 13th (center of No. 1) Streets, showing separate phases of this block front which has building units at each corner and a garage in the center thereof. The photographer is viewing in a generally eastward direction from the empty lot on the west side of the Avenue where the former Rhinelander Flats stood. View No. 1 shows an extensive view eastward on the north side of W. 13th Street, midway being the white epistyle of the Greenwich Presbyterian Church. To the east of same is the towering Salvation Army Building, the main entrance of which is on 14th Street.
June 15, 1938.
Views 1,2 and 3
P.L.Sperr

Seventh Avenue, west side, north from W. 12th to 14th Streets, showing mainly a theatre production on the former "Rhinelander Flats" site, extending between 12th and 13th Streets. Occupying the next block to the north are two structures: one, the Metropolitan Temple, and the other a modern apartment house.
View No. 2 of this set shows at the N.W. corner of 12th Street, a newspaper stand, a subway entrance (I.R.T) and the Federal Theatre bill board.

August 11, 1938.
Views 1 and 2
